							<div class="comment-author vcard"><img alt='' src='http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/ef178954261362b92d4c2ce30290b065?s=32&#038;d=http%3A%2F%2F2.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D32&#038;r=X' class='photo avatar avatar-32' height='32' width='32' /> <span class="fn n">Alex C</span></div>
							<div class="comment-meta">Posted May 24, 2012 at 12:12 pm <span class="meta-sep">|</span> <a href="#comment-3086" title="Permalink to this comment">Permalink</a> | <a class='comment-reply-link' href='/the-case-against-lady-gaga/?replytocom=3086#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-3086", "3086", "respond", "9")'>Reply</a></div>
<p>Of course Lady Gaga is a lie. Thank goodness. Can you imagine an artist who simply gets up there and dutifully reports true facts? That would be rather boring, wouldn&#8217;t it? Being an artist is a creative endeavor, after all. Lies are fiction, truths are non-fiction.</p>
<p>I think it&#8217;s funny how Lady Gaga&#8217;s detractors feel that their puritan ethics of pop stardom have been torn asunder by her.</p>
<p>Artists like Bowie are totally safe and mainstream today. Their work is in the museum of acceptable history. While Bowie was controversial (about as reviled as he was admired) in the &#8217;70s, almost no one today is repulsed or shocked by his old images and statements. As for Madonna, she was a corporate hustler from day one &#8230;</p>
